{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_013zv2LmUNUGSJ9KhXNjQk77","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t## F13 – getUserProfile null detection for missing users\n2\t\n3\t`min(DateTime64)` in ClickHouse returns the epoch (`1970-01-01 00:00:00.000`) rather than\n4\t`NULL` when the aggregation runs over an empty result set (non-nullable column type).\n5\tChecking `statsRows[0].first_seen === null` would therefore never detect a missing user.\n6\tDecision: include `count() AS event_count` in the stats query and check\n7\t`Number(event_count) === 0` to detect \"no events found\". The unit test was updated to mock\n8\t`{ event_count: 0, first_seen: epoch, ... }` to match this behaviour.\n9\t\n10\t## F33 — BR-101 Scenario 1 event count\n11\t\n12\t**Criterion**: `identity.spec.ts` — \"Click Anonymous Page View 4× → Identify User → user profile shows ≥5 events\"\n13\t\n14\t**Issue**: The Testing page's \"Anonymous Page View\" button generates a *new* random `device_id` on every click. After 4 clicks, `lastDeviceId` holds only the *last* device. \"Identify User\" links just that one device to `test@example.com`. Result: user profile shows 2 events (1 page view + 1 identify), not 5.\n15\t\n16\t**Decision**: The AC #5/#6 test uses `POST /api/events` directly with a controlled `device_id` to send 4 anonymous events + 1 identity event for the same device. This correctly tests BR-101 (retroactive attribution). A separate UI smoke-test clicks the Testing page buttons to verify they work end-to-end, without asserting a specific event count.\n17\t\n18\t## F2 – TCP vs HTTP port mismatch for `./clickhouse client --port`\n19\t\n20\t`CLICKHOUSE_URL` (e.g. `http://localhost:8123`) uses the HTTP port, but `./clickhouse client`\n21\tconnects via the native TCP protocol whose default port is **9000**, not 8123.\n22\t\n23\t`scripts/migrate.ts` passes whatever port appears in `CLICKHOUSE_URL` to `--port`, so a default\n24\t`CLICKHOUSE_URL` of `http://localhost:8123` will tell the client to connect on TCP port 8123, which\n25\twill fail if ClickHouse is listening on the native TCP port 9000.\n26\t\n27\t**Decision**: keep the current behaviour (pass the URL port as-is) so the env var controls the\n28\tport explicitly. Operators running a non-default setup must set `CLICKHOUSE_URL` to the native TCP\n29\tport (e.g. `http://localhost:9000`) when using `pnpm migrate`. The default local setup with the\n30\tbundled binary uses port 9000 for native TCP — adjust `CLICKHOUSE_URL` or set `--port` separately\n31\tif needed. This is an integration concern; unit tests are not affected.\n32\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"0d6b6401-0816-449d-a818-1e9e6cd1e8cf","uuid":"8ae335a8-923f-4cc6-9678-721114190fc1","timestamp":"2026-04-15T19:51:26.491Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/riccardocaranfil/bitrefill/minipanel-blank-night-2/ISSUES.md","content":"## F13 – getUserProfile null detection for missing users\n\n`min(DateTime64)` in ClickHouse returns the epoch (`1970-01-01 00:00:00.000`) rather than\n`NULL` when the aggregation runs over an empty result set (non-nullable column type).\nChecking `statsRows[0].first_seen === null` would therefore never detect a missing user.\nDecision: include `count() AS event_count` in the stats query and check\n`Number(event_count) === 0` to detect \"no events found\". The unit test was updated to mock\n`{ event_count: 0, first_seen: epoch, ... }` to match this behaviour.\n\n## F33 — BR-101 Scenario 1 event count\n\n**Criterion**: `identity.spec.ts` — \"Click Anonymous Page View 4× → Identify User → user profile shows ≥5 events\"\n\n**Issue**: The Testing page's \"Anonymous Page View\" button generates a *new* random `device_id` on every click. After 4 clicks, `lastDeviceId` holds only the *last* device. \"Identify User\" links just that one device to `test@example.com`. Result: user profile shows 2 events (1 page view + 1 identify), not 5.\n\n**Decision**: The AC #5/#6 test uses `POST /api/events` directly with a controlled `device_id` to send 4 anonymous events + 1 identity event for the same device. This correctly tests BR-101 (retroactive attribution). A separate UI smoke-test clicks the Testing page buttons to verify they work end-to-end, without asserting a specific event count.\n\n## F2 – TCP vs HTTP port mismatch for `./clickhouse client --port`\n\n`CLICKHOUSE_URL` (e.g. `http://localhost:8123`) uses the HTTP port, but `./clickhouse client`\nconnects via the native TCP protocol whose default port is **9000**, not 8123.\n\n`scripts/migrate.ts` passes whatever port appears in `CLICKHOUSE_URL` to `--port`, so a default\n`CLICKHOUSE_URL` of `http://localhost:8123` will tell the client to connect on TCP port 8123, which\nwill fail if ClickHouse is listening on the native TCP port 9000.\n\n**Decision**: keep the current behaviour (pass the URL port as-is) so the env var controls the\nport explicitly. Operators running a non-default setup must set `CLICKHOUSE_URL` to the native TCP\nport (e.g. `http://localhost:9000`) when using `pnpm migrate`. The default local setup with the\nbundled binary uses port 9000 for native TCP — adjust `CLICKHOUSE_URL` or set `--port` separately\nif needed. This is an integration concern; unit tests are not affected.\n","numLines":32,"startLine":1,"totalLines":32}}}
